{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:55:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:55:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18939"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.64,0.05,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91048"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5878"},{"type":"tags","id":"5881"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following an unwitnessed syncopal episode at home. His wife heard a loud noise from the kitchen and found him on the floor. He has no recollection of the event. He reports reduced appetite and energy levels over the past few weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes hypertension, moderate aortic stenosis diagnosed three years ago, and depression. His medications include perindopril and sertraline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His heart rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg supine and 125/80 mmHg standing, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals an ejection systolic murmur, loudest at the right upper sternal edge with radiation to the carotids. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show sodium 138 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), creatinine 85 \u00b5mol/L (60-110), haemoglobin 135 g/L (130-175).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG shows normal sinus rhythm. Computed tomography of the brain is unremarkable with no evidence of intracranial haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation for the most likely cause of his collapse?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carotid doppler ultrasound","Transthoracic echocardiogram","Tilt table test","Exercise stress test","24-hour Holter monitor"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an elderly man with known aortic stenosis who has experienced syncope, which is a concerning development that may indicate disease progression. The presence of recent constitutional symptoms (reduced appetite and energy) further supports this possibility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it will assess the severity of aortic stenosis, which may have progressed since his previous assessment. Syncope in aortic stenosis typically occurs due to inability to increase cardiac output during exertion, and its occurrence is associated with poor prognosis if left untreated. Aortic stenosis is the most common structural cause of cardiac syncope, and can be successfully treated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to detect intermittent arrhythmias, but given the known aortic stenosis and recent symptoms, assessing valve function should take priority. Holter monitoring should still be considered as a subsequent investigation if the echocardiogram is non-contributory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there were focal neurological symptoms or carotid bruits on examination. The clinical presentation is more consistent with cardiac syncope than a transient ischaemic attack.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETilt table testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose vasovagal syncope, which typically occurs with prolonged standing and is preceded by prodromal symptoms. While there is a small postural drop in blood pressure, the context of known aortic stenosis makes cardiac syncope more likely than orthostatic hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise stress testing\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in symptomatic severe aortic stenosis due to the risk of sudden cardiac death. The severity of aortic stenosis should be assessed first with an echocardiogram before considering any form of stress testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac syncope should be suspected in elderly patients with aortic stenosis presenting with unwitnessed falls or syncope.","Echocardiogram is essential in evaluating the severity of aortic stenosis when syncope occurs.","Recent onset of reduced appetite and energy may indicate progression of aortic stenosis severity."],"references":["Wong CW. Complexity of syncope in elderly people: a comprehensive geriatric approach. Hong Kong medical journal. 2018 Apr 1;24(2):182. Available online at ; https://www.hkmj.org/system/files/hkmj176945.pdf","Adams HS, Ashokkumar S, Newcomb A, MacIsaac AI, Whitbourn RJ, Palmer S. Contemporary review of severe aortic stenosis. Internal Medicine Journal. 2019 Mar;49(3):297-305. Available online at ; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/imj.14071"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91048"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91048"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T18:56:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T19:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11673"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree"